ol.li:
We solve the equation for y in terms of x.
            \begin{align*}
                −3y =6 − 4x
                y = \frac{6 − 4x}{-3}
                =\frac{6}{-3}+\frac{-4x}{-3}
                y = -2+\frac{4}{3}x
            \end{align*}

We see that the slope of the line is m = \frac{4}{3} and its y-intercept is b = −2. We begin by plotting the y-intercept, (0, −2). We then use the slope to find another point on the line. We have
        m = \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{4}{3}
        so starting at (0, −2), we move 4 units in the y-direction and 3 units in the x-direction, to arrive at the point (3, 2). Finally, we draw the line through these two points. (See .)

sidebyside.p:
The line crosses the y-axis at the point (0, 3200), so the y-intercept is 3200. To calculate the slope of the line, locate another point, say (20, 6000), and compute:
\begin{align*}m = \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}
    = \frac{6000 − 3200}{20 − 0}
    =\frac{2800}{20}= 140
\end{align*}
The slope-intercept form of the equation, with m = 140 and b = 3200, is y = 3200 + 140x.

